Implement the private `do_add_edge/3` function.

`do_add_edge(state, from, to)` is the pure graph-mutation helper behind the
`{:add_edge, from, to}` server call. It must validate the edge and, only if the
edge is legal, produce an updated graph state. Specifically:

- First ensure both endpoints exist in the graph. Validate `from` and then `to`
  using `require_vertex/2` (which returns `:ok` when the vertex is present, or
  `{:error, :vertex_not_found}` otherwise).
- Then ensure the edge would not introduce a cycle, using
  `check_no_cycle/3` (which returns `:ok` when safe, `{:error, :cycle}` when the
  edge from `from` to `to` — including a self-loop — would create a cycle).
- If all three checks pass, build the new state by adding `to` to the successor
  set of `from` in `out_edges` and adding `from` to the predecessor set of `to`
  in `in_edges` (both via `Map.update!/3` with `MapSet.put/2`), and return
  `{:ok, new_state}`.
- If any check fails, the corresponding `{:error, reason}` tuple must propagate
  out unchanged and the state must not be modified.

Use a `with` expression so the first failing check short-circuits and its error
tuple becomes the return value.

